    "analysis": "We have already computed global p5/p50/p95 for candidate component-KPI series and flagged in-window anomalies (noting that constant-zero series produce misleading flags). From the aggregated anomaly counts, the largest anomaly counts are: user:error (25, but constant-zero), catalogue:socket (22 anomalies, values below normal), payment:socket (22 anomalies, values below normal), payment:diskio (14 anomalies, many zeros / extreme p95), orders:latency (5 anomalies), carts KPIs (4 anomalies each). Traces and error_logs are empty so we cannot use call chains or error traces. To decide root cause we should identify which component shows: (a) the largest number of distinct KPI-series with anomalies, (b) the largest total anomaly events, and (c) the most severe deviations from thresholds (relative severity). That will let us pick the predominant faulty service-level component. Note: we must exclude or downweight constant-zero series (p5==p95==0) since they artifactually flag equality as anomaly.\nWhat’s next: compute per-component aggregates (for components carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user) over the incident window using the global thresholds computed on the full series: total anomaly events (count), number of KPI-series with anomalies, earliest anomaly timestamp, and per-component max relative severity (for each anomaly compute severity = abs(value - nearest_threshold)/max(abs(nearest_threshold), small_eps) where nearest_threshold is p95 if value>=p95 else p5 if value<=p5; use eps=1e-9 and report as ratio). Also provide top 3 (kpi_name, anomaly_count, max_severity, earliest_anomaly_iso) per component. This will help choose the root-cause component and reason.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For components [\"carts\",\"catalogue\",\"orders\",\"payment\",\"user\"]: 1) Recompute global p5,p50,p95 per (cmdb_id,kpi_name) using the full metric.csv series (do NOT filter by time). 2) Filter metric.csv to the incident window 2024-01-20T14:06:53Z→2024-01-20T14:36:53Z. 3) For each in-window metric row determine if it's an anomaly: value >= p95 OR value <= p5 (use equality). Exclude KPI-series where p5==p95==0 from counting as anomalies (i.e., treat their in-window anomalies as non-anomalous for this step). 4) For each anomaly compute severity = abs(value - threshold)/max(abs(threshold),1e-9) where threshold = p95 if value>=p95 else p5. 5) Aggregate per component: total_anomaly_events (sum), num_kpi_series_with_anomaly, earliest_anomaly_iso (min), max_severity. 6) For each component, list top 3 KPI series by anomaly count with columns (kpi_name, anomaly_count, max_severity, earliest_anomaly_iso). Return a compact table of the 5 components sorted by total_anomaly_events desc; round severity ratios to 3 decimals and limit shown example rows to keep output compact."}

